entry.title: [AsyncSB] Separate ShouldSkipRequestCheck from UrlCheckerOnSB
entry.content:
Previously url_checker_delegate->ShouldSkipRequestCheck is coupled

inside UrlCheckerOnSB. To support async Safe Browsing check, we will

create two UrlCheckerOnSBs in BrowserUrlLoaderThrottle: one for

sync check and one for async check. This means that

ShouldSkipRequestCheck will be called twice, which is redundant since

whether a check is skipped is irrelevant to whether the check is async

or not.



This CL creates a helper class in BrowserUrlLoaderThrottle that is

responsible to perform the skip request check once for both checkers.

The extra class is needed because the check needs to be performed on the

SB thread, which may or may not be on the same thread of

BrowserUrlLoaderThrottle.



Specifically this CL contains the following behavioral changes:

* GetDelegateCallback is changed from OnceCallback to

RepeatingCallback. The callback is called twice:

UrlCheckerOnSB (existing) and SkipCheckCheckerOnSB (new).

* There could be an extra thread hop before BULT calls UrlCheckerOnSB.

This is because the skip request check can only be done on the SB

thread. Since kSafeBrowsingOnUIThread will soon be enabled by

default, there won't be any real thread hop in practice.



Related CL comment: https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5051861/comment/685e960a_9d4998ad/

entry.title: [Extensions] Duct tape a crash in --pack-extension
entry.content:
--pack-extension allows a user (or, more likely, tool) to pack

an extension from the commandline. This works by short-circuiting

the browser startup process, packing the extension, and early-returning

from the main loop in Chrome.



This happens *before* the base::FeatureList is initialized. Prior to

https://crrev.com/ca7b5601102d, checking the state of a feature before

feature list initialization would return the default value. Now, it

crashes.



In this CL, change the checks that happen in SimpleFeature and friends

to check the state of the feature if the FeatureList is initialized and,

if not, fall back to the default state of the feature. This is okay in

the pack extension case because we still have all the same checks in

place when *using* the extension and it's already trivially possible to

pack an extension with any conceivable feature state (by just appending

commandline flags).



This is only a band-aid fix for the issue. This will still crash if any

of the ManifestHandlers or other extension-creation mechanisms use

base::FeatureList::IsEnabled() before feature list initialization. The

right fix here is to move the pack extension job after the

FeatureList is initialized so that we don't have to have these hacks

in place; however, that's non-trivial due to other issues that come up

when we try to delay pack-extension handling. We'll look into fixing

this more properly in a follow-up, but this should at least prevent

crashing in many of the cases.



Add a browsertest that repros the bug and verifies the fix.

entry.title: ios: Fix status bar startup flicker.
entry.content:
Previously startup would call:

[window makeKeyAndVisible];

which shows the status bar.



Then to work around crbug.com/850387

self.window.rootViewController = self.baseViewController

which hides the status bar.



And then finally startup calls:

self.mainInterface.userInteractionEnabled = YES

which triggers:

[self setNeedsStatusBarAppearanceUpdate];

which shows the status bar.



The fix is to defer -makeKeyAndVisible until after

[self.mainCoordinator start], which contains the workaround.



Includes a killswitch, since this is a somewhat delicate area of

startup.

entry.title: Abstract OpenXR Hand Joint Data parsing
entry.content:
Move the OpenXR HandTracker logic out of openxr_controller and into a

delegated class. This helps to encapsulate the various static asserts

that were being made there, as well as provides an avenue towards

potential future flexibility to parse gestures out from additional

hand tracker related extensions. (https://crrev.com/c/5047184 is one

such example of a proposal to do this.)



Also updates and clarifies the requirements for enabling the hand-input

feature; namely that we need the XR_EXT_HAND_TRACKING extension to be

enabled to get the hand data *and* we need an extension that can

generate a "primary interaction" for that hand to be enabled (of which

there is currently only the XR_MSFT_HAND_INTERACTION).

entry.content:
Ash-specific code shouldn't be relied on from Desktop UIs, even on

ChromeOS. Ash WebUI and Browser WebUI are not guaranteed to have the

same look and feel in all cases, as design (and sometimes infra

patterns) may differ between the two. As a result, Browser UIs

importing Ash WebUI files risk ending up with mismatched design and/or

infra patterns.

code that uses ts_library, and add lists of current exceptions to this

rule which should be fixed (settings, inline login).

entry.title: [layout] Add N-way measure cache.
entry.content:
Some layout modes (grid) will measure an element multiple times with

different constraints. For example grid has two passes for determining

row sizes, and during these two steps we may have two different

inline-sizes. On top of this we have measures for orthogonal min/max

sizes, and baselines.



If we end up in one of these cases, we can have exponential layout

time costs as we'll constantly miss the measure cache.



Introduce a LRU cache to handle this scenario - and allow adding to

this cache when side-effects are disabled.

We have a DCHECK that asserts that the "wire type" of the protobuf tag

ID must be length delimited, which is only true if bytes fed to the

parser is a valid serialization of the `StreamBody` protobuf. In fuzzer,

arbitrary bytes are fed to the parser, which sometimes fails the DCHECK.



This CL fixes the fuzzer issue by making the parser close the stream

when an unexpected wire type is found, rather than DCHECK it.

entry.title: media: Add ARM secure codecs support
entry.content:
This reworks the existing change for H264 secure playback on ARM to pass

the secure_handle through the picture creation method, and attach it to

the picture rather than passing it through SetStream. This is more

compatible with VP9/AV1 codecs and removes the state tracking in the

accelerator.



In order to avoid having to modify all the windows/mac code as well, we

are doing this through an additional method on the accelerator

interface. We will be able to drop this new method once we switch to the

new flat V4L2 stateless decoder as that won't be tying input buffers to

output surfaces anymore. Then we can just put it in media::CodecPicture

and set that one field in the XXXDecoder and then the accelerator can

use it after that.

development still on the kernel/TEE side

entry.title: [Read Anything] Include unignored headings that lie outside of the
entry.content:
main node.



We keep headings that are found where the tree also contains a main

or article node. Why not keep heading nodes, regardless of whether a

main or article node is found? Most pages probably have a heading node

of some sort. Even un-distillable pages like Calendar which would just

display the heading and then little else. So if we always keep heading

nodes, then users will probably never see the zero state page which

instructs them to select-to-distill. In order to keep the instructions

for this feature (and make un-distillable pages meaningful in reading

mode), we don't keep heading modes that are found without an

accompanying main and article node.
